a hybrid environment.

529
00:21:45,840 --> 00:21:49,230
So we've used the existing AWS
route server functionality,

530
00:21:49,230 --> 00:21:52,740
think of it as a BGP
propagation mechanism.

531
00:21:52,740 --> 00:21:55,110
What it does is you've got a lot of IPs,

532
00:21:55,110 --> 00:21:57,450
underlay IPs, overlay IPs, et cetera.

533
00:21:57,450 --> 00:22:02,250
This is like your VM IP
spaces or your appliance IPs,

534
00:22:02,250 --> 00:22:06,240
so the route server basically
enables BGP communication.

535
00:22:06,240 --> 00:22:09,090
It acts as a BGP endpoint
between your NSX Edge

536
00:22:09,090 --> 00:22:11,910
and all your route tables,
propagates your route table

537
00:22:11,910 --> 00:22:14,460
so you don't have to worry
about any of those failovers,

538
00:22:14,460 --> 00:22:17,640
or like IP addressing going
in and adding static routes

539
00:22:17,640 --> 00:22:18,843
into your route table.

540
00:22:21,150 --> 00:22:22,260
And if you take a step back

541
00:22:22,260 --> 00:22:24,780
of the full external connectivity,

542
00:22:24,780 --> 00:22:27,700
you can have multiple EVS environments

543
00:22:28,950 --> 00:22:30,510
as part of inner region.

544
00:22:30,510 --> 00:22:31,980
You can also have other workloads

545
00:22:31,980 --> 00:22:34,770
that you're running within
the same VPC as well.

546
00:22:34,770 --> 00:22:36,450
And then I mentioned, all this connects

547
00:22:36,450 --> 00:22:38,790
into a transit gateway.

548
00:22:38,790 --> 00:22:40,230
And then from the transit gateway,

549
00:22:40,230 --> 00:22:42,210
you could either have a direct connect

550
00:22:42,210 --> 00:22:46,260
or a VPN connection back to
your on-premises network.

551
00:22:46,260 --> 00:22:49,263
So it enables the full
end-to-end connectivity.

